Research consistently shows:

# Inferential Thinking

depends on:

```text id="m5i2qe"
evidence
and
background knowledge
```

Inference is NOT:

```text id="r8i6qe"
guessing
without
support
```

Students learn:

```text id="x2i9qe"
read text
→ notice clues
→ connect prior knowledge
→ infer meaning
→ support with evidence
```

This develops:

* deep comprehension
* reasoning
* interpretation
* critical thinking
* evidence use

This becomes:

# Evidence-Based Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p3i4qe"
inference
=
personal opinion
```

or:

```text id="u7i1qe"
answers
must be
stated
directly
```

Some may think:

```text id="c9i5qe"
text evidence
=
copying
whole passage
```

without understanding:

```text id="k4i8qe"
evidence
supports
thinking
```

Students may also:

```text id="n6i3qe"
ignore
important clues
```

Example:

text says:

```text id="t1i7qe"
Sam grabbed
his umbrella
and hurried
outside
```

students may answer:

```text id="q5i2qe"
Sam likes umbrellas
```

instead of inferring:

```text id="v8i4qe"
it may
be raining
```

because:

```text id="w3i7qe"
clues
and
reasoning
matter
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="a9i1qe"
supported inference
```

For Grade 5:

focus includes:

Text Evidence:

* quotations
* paraphrasing
* supporting details
* proof
* relevant clues

Inference:

* implied meaning
* character reasoning
* prediction
* cause-effect
* author hints

Important idea:

```text id="g6i5rx"
good inferences
need
evidence
```

